":["English: habitational name from Aylesbury (Buckinghamshire), from an Old English personal name <i>Ægel</i> (genitive <i>Ægeles</i>, <i>Ægles</i>) + <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place’ (dative <i>byrig</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter Aylesbury was born about 1265, in Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England, his father, William Aylesbury, was 24 and his mother, Mrs William Aylesbury, was 22. He married Cecilia Somery in 1287, in Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died after 1292, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1265–after 1292":"umbes 1265–pärast 1292","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1257–1361":"1257–1361","1276–1349":"1276–1349","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1242–1274":"1242–1274","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","about 1292":"umbes 1292","after 1292":"pärast 1292","1264":"1264","1242":"1242","1274":"1274","1361":"1361","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1257":"1257","1278":"1278","Abt 1276":"umbes 1276","1244":"1244","1287":"1287","1276":"1276","1265":"1265","about 1265":"umbes 1265","